===Switch to boxing===
Woodhouse had a history of [[theft]], [[robbery]] and [[affray]] and admitted to have been involved in around 100 [[street fighting|street fights]].<ref name="Woodhouse emerges as a Diamond from the rough">{{cite news
| title = Woodhouse emerges as a Diamond from the rough
| url = http://www.guardian.co.uk/sport/2006/dec/11/boxing.football
| publisher = The Guardian
| first = David | last = Ornstein
| date = [[2006-12-11]]
| accessdate = 2008-09-16}}</ref> He said; "Boxing has always been my first love, even as a kid",<ref name="Woodhouse poised for boxing debut" /> and "I love fighting...Rather than get locked up for it, I might as well get paid for it."<ref name="Boxing: Woodhouse glove affair kick-starts new career">{{cite news
| title = Boxing: Woodhouse glove affair kick-starts new career
| url =  http://www.timesonline.co.uk/tol/sport/more_sport/article631945.ece
| publisher = The Times
| first = Ron | last = Lewis
| date = [[2006-09-08]]
| accessdate = 2008-09-16}}</ref> He also stated that he used to [[sparring|spar]] in the boxing gym after football training without his manager knowledge,<ref name="Woodhouse poised for boxing debut">{{cite news
| title = Woodhouse poised for boxing debut
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/boxing/5275398.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = [[2006-08-22]]
| accessdate = 2008-09-16}}</ref> saying "A few times at Sheffield United, [[Neil Warnock]] would drag me in and say <U+2018>I hear you<U+2019>ve been boxing<U+2019>. I<U+2019>d be standing there with a big black eye and a fat lip and deny it."<ref name="Boxing: Woodhouse glove affair kick-starts new career" /> He trained under former British featherweight champion, [[Gary De Roux]],<ref name="Boxing: Woodhouse glove affair kick-starts new career" /> and made his boxing debut on 8 September 2006 at [[Grosvenor House Hotel]], [[London]], in a [[welterweight]] contest against [[Dean Marcantonio]]. The former footballer had lost two [[Stone (mass)|stone]] in weight since his playing days with [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]].<ref name="Boxing: Woodhouse marks debut with thumping win">{{cite news
| title = Boxing: Woodhouse marks debut with thumping win
| url = http://www.independent.co.uk/sport/general/boxing-woodhouse-marks-debut-with-thumping-win-415280.html
| publisher = The Independent
| first = Steve | last = Bunce
| date = [[2006-09-09]]
| accessdate = 2008-09-16}}</ref> The fight was scheduled for four rounds of two minutes, Woodhouse knocked his opponent down twice in the final round and won on points.<ref name="Boxing: Woodhouse marks debut with thumping win" /><ref name="boxrec">{{cite news
| title = Curtis Woodhouse
| url = http://www.boxrec.com/list_bouts.php?human_id=368372&cat=boxer
| publisher = Box Rec
| accessdate = 2008-09-16}}</ref>

===Return to football and ban from boxing===
After only one professional fight, Woodhouse returned to football in November 2006, signing for [[Rushden & Diamonds F.C.|Rushden & Diamonds]] who played in the highest-tier of [[non-league football]] in the [[Conference National]].<ref name="Club announcement: New signing">{{cite news
| title = Club Announcement: New Signing
| url = http://www.thediamondsfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10784~933642,00.html
| publisher = Rushden & Diamonds F.C.
| date = [[2006-11-25]]
| accessdate = 2008-09-16}}</ref> His boxing license was suspended by the [[British Boxing Board of Control]], following a conviction for assaulting a police officer whilst drunk and of using threatening, abusive or insulting words or behaviour in April 2006, when he was still playing for [[Grimsby Town F.C.|Grimsby Town]],<ref name="Woodhouse emerges as a Diamond from the rough" /><ref name="Woodhouse makes football comeback">{{cite news
| title = Woodhouse makes football comeback
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rushden_and_diamonds/6185620.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = [[2006-11-26]]
| accessdate = 2007-03-02}}</ref> and not under the BBBofC's jurisdiction at the time of the incident. He was ordered to pay <U+00A3>100 compensation to PC Andrew Whitehead and <U+00A3>350 in costs. Woodhouse chose to play for Rushden & Diamonds to fulfil a promise he made to someone who was part of the consortium that took over the [[Irthlingborough]] based club.<ref name="Woodhouse emerges as a Diamond from the rough" /> He made his debut against [[Aldershot Town F.C.|Aldershot Town]] on 25 November 2006, in the 1&ndash;0 defeat.<ref name="Woodhouse makes football comeback" /> He made five appearances in the [[Conference National]] for Rushden,<ref name="soccerbase" /> before deciding to leave to concentrate on his boxing career.<ref name="Woodhouse and Rigby leave Diamonds">{{cite news
| title = Woodhouse and Rigby leave Diamonds
| url = http://www.thediamondsfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10784~962210,00.html
| publisher = Rushden & Diamonds F.C.
| date = [[2007-01-08]]
| accessdate = 2008-09-16}}</ref>

He then returned to Rushden on 1 March 2007,<ref name="Woodhouse re-signs for Diamonds">{{cite news
| title = Woodhouse re-signs for Diamonds
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rushden_and_diamonds/6409521.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = [[2007-03-01]]
| accessdate = 2007-03-02}}</ref><ref name="Woodhouse returns to Nene Park">{{cite news
| title = Woodhouse returns to Nene Park
| url = http://www.thediamondsfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/NewsDetail/0,,10784~989622,00.html
| publisher = Rushden & Diamonds F.C.
| date = [[2007-03-02]]
| accessdate = 2008-09-16}}</ref> and made a further 11 appearances in the Conference in the [[2006-07 in English football|2006&ndash;07]] season,<ref name="soccerbase" /> scoring three goals,<ref name="soccerbase 2">{{cite news
| title = Woodhouse
| url = http://www.soccerbase.com/players_details.sd?playerid=45673
| publisher = Soccerbase
| accessdate = 2008-09-16}}</ref> including a 30-yard long range effort against [[Northwich Victoria F.C.|Northwich Victoria]] on 23 April 2007.<ref name="Woodhouse adds to Vics' woes">{{cite news
| title = Woodhouse adds to Vics' woes
| url = http://www.nonleaguedaily.com/news/index.php?newsmode=FULL&nid=41842
| publisher = Non-LeagueDaily.com
| date = [[2007-04-24]]
| accessdate = 2008-09-16}}</ref> After five months out, Woodhouse returned to the ring for his second fight on 15 April 2007, defeating [[Duncan Cottier]] on points after four rounds.<ref name="boxrec" /> On 1 May 2007, he signed a new two-year deal with Rushden & Diamonds.<ref name="Woodhouse signs new Diamonds deal">{{cite news
| title = Woodhouse signs new Diamonds deal
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rushden_and_diamonds/6612389.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = [[2007-05-01]]
| accessdate = 2007-05-10}}</ref> He then defeated [[Peter Dunn (boxer)|Peter Dunn]] in a bout on 3 June 2007, again on points, in a contest of four three minute rounds.<ref name="boxrec" /> In his fourth fight on 5 December 2007, he defeated [[Craig Tomes]] by way of [[knock-out]] after just 1 minute and 27 seconds, landing a left [[Hook (boxing)|hook]] that unsettled Tomes as the referee decided his opponent as unfit to continue.<ref name="Footballer-turned-boxer Curtis Woodhouse is a real knockout now">{{cite news
| title = Footballer-turned-boxer Curtis Woodhouse is a real knockout now
| url = http://www.sportingo.com/sports/a6040_footballerturnedboxer-curtis-woodhouse-real-knockout
| publisher = Sportingo
| first = Mark | last = White
| date = [[2007-12-08]]
| accessdate = 2008-09-16}}</ref> [[Matt Seawright]] was Woodhouse's next boxing opponent, he defeated him after Seawright felt he was unable to continue after the third round.<ref name="Diamonds footballer Curtis wins fifth straight boxing match">{{cite news
| title = Diamonds footballer Curtis wins fifth straight boxing match
| url = http://www.northamptonchron.co.uk/sport/Diamonds-footballer-Curtis-wins-fifth.3883338.jp
| publisher = Northampton Chronicle & Echo
| date = [[2007-05-16]]
| accessdate = 2008-09-16}}</ref><ref name="boxrec" /> Woodhouse finished the [[2007-08 in English football|2007&ndash;08]] football season having played in 29 Conference National matches, scoring once and recieving two red cards.<ref name="soccerbase" /> On 17 May 2008, Woodhouse achieved his sixth straight victory, maintaining his undefeated record against [[Dave Murray (boxer)|Dave Murray]] at [[Bramall Lane]], defeating his opponent by knock-out in the second round. Murray managed to beat the [[standing eight count]], but the referee deemed him unable to continue after 1 minute and 23 seconds.<ref name="Woodhouse scores hat trick down at the lane">{{cite news
| title = Woodhouse scores hat trick down at the lane
| url = http://www.britishboxing.net/news_3458-Woodhouse-scores-hat-trick-down-at-the-lane.html
| publisher = BritishBoxing.net
| first = Jim | last = Wright
| date = [[2008-05-18]]
| accessdate = 2008-09-16}}</ref> After defeating [[Wayne Downing]] in 57 seconds on 21 June 2008,<ref name="boxrec"/> Woodhouse stated his intention to retire from football at the end of the [[2008-09 in English football|2008&ndash;09]] season, in order to concentrate on his boxing career.<ref name="I will quit next year - Woodhouse">{{cite news
| title = I will quit next year - Woodhouse
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rushden_and_diamonds/7470228.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = [[2008-06-24]]
| accessdate = 2008-06-29}}</ref> He was later appointed as team captain for his final season at the club.<ref name="Woodhouse named Rushden captain">{{cite news
| title = Woodhouse named Rushden captain
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rushden_and_diamonds/7526852.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = [[2008-07-26]]
| accessdate = 2008-07-26}}</ref> Woodhouse scored a decisive penalty in Rushden's opening game of the 2008&ndash;09 season, away on 9 August 2008, against newly promoted [[Eastbourne Borough F.C.|Eastbourne Borough]].<ref name="Eastbourne 0-1 Rushden">{{cite news
| title = Eastbourne 0-1 Rushden
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/teams/r/rushden_and_diamonds/7526852.stm
| publisher = BBC Sport
| date = [[2008-08-09]]
| accessdate = 2008-09-16}}</ref> He was sent-off again in the home game against [[Histon F.C.|Histon]] on 25 August 2008, after receiving two yellow cards.<ref name="Rushden & Diamonds 1-2 Histon">{{cite news
| title = Rushden & Diamonds 1-2 Histon
| url = http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_conf/7565341.stm
